reviews.text: Awesome Neko-Cafe ! I've been there for five times in 3 trip in Japan ! Small place very cute cats and the people who work there are so kind ! You can see they ALL Loves Cats and take care of them ! As a foreigner I loved been with only Japanese customer. Is not one of the biggest Neko-Cafe in Tokyo but one authentic ! Recommend thousand times !

This is the first Cat Cafe we went to in Tokyo. The place is cozy, warm, and quiet. The cats are well maintained, super cute,  and they varies in size. One of the cats seems to weight 15 lb. We stayed there for half an hour and the cost was about 660 Yen per person and you must purchase a drink. The drink ranges between 350 yen to  500 yen. The drink is small compared to Canada. The place is air conditioned but I wish it's a little bit colder. The cafe has a little bit of cat smell. If you want a cat to play with you, purchase some food and they will come to you immediately!!
Super friendly staff!! The ice coffee au late is so good and the kitties are super cute!

A cute cozy cat cafe with several cats. Employees are helpful and can speak English too. We chose 30 minute option and we have to order a drink each. We also got the cat food which helped bring the cats out to us. The employees also go through a guide to make sure we have a good experience.

We chose this cafe for the google maps rating and we regretted it. The place is not clean and although the cats looked healthy, the room is tiny and packed with nineteen cats. As cat lovers, after this experience we will never return to this cafe or any other cat cafe. We made a mistake.

reviews.text: The kitties here are all very cute and well-behaved. The cats are, of course, not very cuddly in my opinion. Although I completely understand why. But they'll happily be petted if you manage to find one asleep or staying still. The space itself is very wide and there are large play areas for the cats and for kids! This is one of the few cat cafés that allow young children. There is also usually a short wait on weekends.
Very nice cat cafe! They allow children in here. Some cat cafes around Tokyo do not. The cats are sweet and very clean. The staff are accommodating as well. They don’t speak much English though.

My wife, daughter and I had a good time here. This was our first visit to a cat café in Japan, and we were pleasantly surprised by how much fun we had. Free drinks, games and mobile device charging was offered but what really set this place apart from the other cat cafes was that they allowed children where most others we visited turned us away as these cafes are seen as relaxation spots in Japan and a child could understandably disrupt that.
It's a lovely cat cafe to go with kids! You can get tea or coffee from the vending machine too. A lot of restaurants around that area!
So many happy cute kitties. Comfortable and quiet. Well worth the reasonable cost.

reviews.text: Beautiful place to drink a coffee or eat while you are enjoying the feline company. The best cat Cafe that I visited in Japan. A huge advantage in addition to the fairy tale atmosphere is there are no time limit.  Definitely worth the visit. Excellent service and the friendly staff handle the cats in the best way possible to allow the customers and cats spend a good time together. I loved it!!

I love cat cares and have been to many, this is a favorite. I like their service fees and that it's not paid by the hour. Great variety of cats, some playful some sweet, most are just indifferent haha! They have have a nice menu of food which is a plus if you stay for hours like I did. There is a strong smell of cat litter as you first enter but eventually you get acclimated, something to note.

Worth the visit! The place looks like a mini Ghibli world, the cats are adorable and it seemed that they took a great care of the cats (staffs were full of love when it comes to treating the cats). Didn’t try much menus but price wise it was fine.

!!! 

*Place does not allow children below 10 years old to enter*

This is the best cat cafe I’ve ever been to in Japan. I’ve been to and seen quite a few as well. The decoration is straight out of a Ghibli film! You feel as if you’ve been transported to another era.

September 7, 2017. A really nice relaxing place, with just enough cats for everyone. However, if you wanna really have their full attention, you gotta buy the cat food 😅 (only ¥300). Be quick though, it runs out once the place gets busy (in the afternoon).

reviews.text: Very nice place! Went there on Tuesday morning, there were only three ladies. Cats are well groomed and clean, they also have very silky fur. Free drinks are available inside from the vending machine, there are also cat toys, manga, blankets and nice music. Will definitely go there again. Owner lady was very nice and explained rules well, I could see that she loves her cats very much. Me and my friend got small presents before we left - stickers and candies. And the price is very reasonable.

Very cozy atmosphere, friendly and helpful staff, fluffy playful cats. Loved this cafe. Good price compared to other similar cafes.  They provide free drinks (from vending machine) and small souvenirs when you leave. Definitely worth coming :D

All the cats except the kittens were avoiding human contact. I don't blame them for it. The place had too many visitors and very little space. Before visiting, I assumed the concept of a Cat Cafe would not be cruel because cats are house pets. But after visiting the cafe I am not so sure. Cramped up in a room with people trying to pet them all day long doesn't really suit the independent and moody nature of cats.  Definitely won't be visiting one of these again.

Just got back from a vacation where I visited here twice, both times weekday mornings. Once I had the place to myself, once there were a half-dozen other customers. Small, but great service, cool cats, and free coffee drinks (if only from a vending machine). It was clear that the cats and staff had a good rapport and everyone wanted to be there. When I was the only one there, the staff kept bringing me napping cats to put on my lap, like they wanted to make sure I was getting value-for-money. Fairly English friendly, too. I speak some Japanese, but even if I didn't I could get by here no problem thanks to signage, booklets, and staff.

Something you don't want to miss out on if you're in the area for sure. Free drinks (tea and coffee but also Pepsi and cocoa). The cats are friendly and the staff can speak a little english so you should be fine even if you can't speak Japanese

reviews.text:
Very friendly cats here. It's a tiny space, minimalist.

When we first came in we almost got distracted by the owl cafe on the ground floor. Luckily we kept our cat focus. We were the only guests, so it was a much more relaxed vibe than some other crazy busy cat cafes.

The cats here really like to be patted on the butt for some reason.
The smell was absolutely terrible. I thought that the owner was good at English but no she was not. I don't recommend coming

Friendly owner, cool cats, cheaper than other cat cafes, doesn't feel like they eagerly 'time' you every 10 minutes for your money. Perhaps a bit more crowded and messy than those big cafes, but makes for a friendlier, more personal experience.
800 yen for 1 hour. Cosy cafe located on 6th floor. Many cute nekos.

This small room is everything I wanted a cat cafe to be. The cats are in charge. The woman who runs it, rehomes the cats so they get forever homes. They don't have to play if they dont want to and have places to hide. And everyone visiting loves cats. We don't need a common language.

reviews.text: It was a big experience to me because I love cats. When you arrive you pay the time that you will spend and if you would like take a cup of tea also you have to pay. I chose with the drink my focus were the cats. You will remove your shoes and clean your hands. They have all prepare for them: food, brushes, and you can have a sit and touch them or play with them. Time spent very fast but if I would come back I will visit them.
Nice place, friendly cats, charges are 700 yen first half an hour. Latte 360 yen. Clean place. Good for cats lover

I visited two cat cafes during my latest visit to Japan and while the other cat cafe was newer, better decorated, had prettier cats and was easier to get to, Nyafe Melange was definitely the better cafe!

For one, Nyafe's manager is also the owner of the cats and you can tell she personally cares of all of them. She can tell you about their personalities, likes and dislikes, tricks they might be persuaded (with food) to do. There is a sense of coziness that Nyafe offers. The owner is really welcoming and kind and it feels like you are visiting your crazy cat lady friend's home.

At other cat cafes, it feels like a very manicured experience with many many many rules and worst of all, the cats seem to be forced to 'perform'. At Nyafe, the owner let us know what each cat's boundaries were, some enjoyed pets, some you need to give them their space, and should any of the cats tire of hoomans, there is a back room for them to retreat to.

TIP: If you are visiting later in the day, it might not be worth it to buy snacks for the cats because they are unlikely to be hungry. So snacks would not help buy their affection.

If you end up visiting Nyafe - which I recommend that you do - please say hello to Latte and Mocha, they are Himalayan sisters and if you walk by the right spot, they may hitch a ride on your shoulders
This place is great for cat lovers, very cosy, comfy, friendly

I recommend this one. Most of them do not allow small children. Ours is 2 years old. She could enter for free and for 30 minutes. It is one room, enough cats to pet (not all of them are willing), looks clean, the Hostess is friendly and speaks a bit of English.

reviews.text: An excellent cat cafe experience. It is a small room on the second floor of the building with capacity for only up to 6 people. The cats are very friendly especially after they smell you and get used to your presence. They enjoyed playing with the toys and had a lot of energy. The owner was very sweet and gave us treats for the cats. They have a small selection of teas and coffee for 100¥. It runs 1000¥ per hour which is very reasonable especially considering how few people are allowed into the room. I will definitely return again in the near future.

The woman who operates it is very kind. The tea is good tea. The cats are very playful, but not so much lap cats. They are also very clean and beautiful-you can tell they are well looked after. The cafe itself is very clean and tidy, and protocols are very clear in English and in Japanese. The only "gripe" is it is small and there isn't much table space. However, if you come more to play with the cats than to sit and have a drink, this is just fine.

If you want to have 5 cats all to yourself, then Choosy Cat Cafe is the place to go. Hidden behind the busy streets of Omotesando, this little place is home to some of the most comfortable cats I have seen in Tokyo. One of them is very young and will crawl up your leg as soon as you get there.

Another plus is the owner. The place is owned by one lady, and it is clear that she love her kitties very very much. She will sit with you and help you play with the cats, and if you speak japanese you can have a really nice talk. All in all, this is a wonderful place for those who want to get away from the busy streets.
This café still exists, but it is members only. So I couldnt enter. Pity!
Closed! No more cats, souvenir shop only.

Cute spot for a cat cafe! You pay for every 10 minutes, take your shoes off and use their slipper, they have lockers for your stuff. 

There are two levels, but most are on the top level. There are a ton of cats to play with, most were sleeping when we came, but still relaxing to pet!
Cats are cats as always. They are cute but they are annoyed by humans most of the time. It is so quiet and warm which makes me wanna take a nap with the cats
We stopped in here while walking through Shibuya Crossing. Lots of cats lounging in here. If you go here, pay the extra for the option to offer the cats a snack.

So many beautiful cats and well behaved. You are not allowed to hold them otherwise this would be a perfect place for cat lovers. Note for things you are not allowed to do: Not allowed to feed them with your own foods, No chasing the cats, No holding them! 
This place is located on the 8th floor and can be access with the elevator. Treat for cat are available for purchased there!

Refused my family of 4 entry because of our youngest, told us to leave her outside, wouldnt even let me wait with her at reception so my wife and older daughter could go sit with the cats. Staff very rude. Awful!

reviews.text: Very warm and quiet environment. Staff were friendly and helpful. I see that many of the reviews here mention that they were not allowed in because they didn't bring their passports, while it was specifically mentioned on the website that this was a requirement when entering so do not complain when the reason for your experience was your own lack of research. The rules were strict to ensure that the cats were treated well and many of the cats were sweet and happy to play. The food was also quite nice! A nice place to visit, would definitely recommend.

Nice cafe. They have strict rules to ensure that human-cat interaction doesn't overly stress out the cats (no picking up of cats, no feeding of certain cats with special needs), which I appreciate, and the staff monitor the humans carefully to help look out for the cats. You can buy snacks for the cats, which is cooked chicken (another plus: instead of dried kibble, it's plain chicken that they've cooked). Can get very crowded because of its easy location, so you might come for the cats, but be prepared for a lot of humans competing for their attention :) Tip: they feed the cats at 1730hrs, and if you're around they let you feed the cats. You'll be very popular with the cats then :)
You can only pet the cats, not hold them. There is no Coffee... so kinda strange. It is a room with cats... . It was ok, but kinda silly, this coming from a cat lover. Good energy there, tho.
Cats seemed to have plenty of space and ways to keep themselves stimulated. Staff was very attentive to the guests and cats. Nice and relaxed.
Nice cats but make sure to buy the cat candy (chicken?) if you want to cusdle as the cats are mostly on the hunt for food. Good price and lots of happy cats!

Cozy and homey cat cafe across two floors starting on 4F. Cats vary from relaxed to playful and atmosphere is very quiet and relaxing. Kids are welcome.
A must go for cat enthusiast. Very calm atmosphere.
Supposed to be a cozy place, but I did not feel like 'at home'. It's quite dirty...

Cozy and cheap cat cafe near the Don Quixote in Akihabara. The place is larger than I expected, with plenty of cats that are really friendly. If you're looking to get the cats' attention, order a coffee and try to open the milk or sugar!

19 cute and beautiful cats. Very nice and quiet. Very clean too.

Cat,cat,cat!!!!
Here is the heaven for cat lovers‼︎ fee is 200yen every 10 mins.

Sadly all cats are heavily sedated, so much they hardly notice anything. Most of them simply stayed sleeping while we were there, and certainly no cat was awake enough to play. The interior is nice, but I wouldn't return.

This was the first cat cafe I've been to but I preferred the second one I went to. Still, this one was cozy and clean.  It is located high up so decent view.  The cats will not be interested in you unless you buy the cat food for 400 yen. That was worth it because once we bought that they swarmed us.  

Not crowded when we went.  We had the place to ourselves most of the time.

There is a 30 minute limit but they do not require you to all buy food.

Great location. Beautiful cats. Maine coon and Norwegian forest cats were a little temperamental but all the others were super friendly.
The guy, I presume owner, very friendly and good English and definitely loved his cats.
Well priced also.
Will return

Those cats were GORJ! And they love their owner. A teensy but pricier, but the atmosphere was really good. And the drinks were made on site and really tasty! Not a bad spot on a quiet afternoon to pass a half an hour.
The cats were all happy and healthy, the place was beautiful and really clean. The food was delicious too and everything was reasonably priced. Definitely a great cat cafe to go to :)
Cat is cute, but they are all sleep >"

reviews.text: Two years in a row and still totally worth it. There is a kitty with short legs that I've seen it growing from a year to another. She is pretty cute. Bear in mind to avoid the rush ours. Best time is early in the morning, when the kittens have energy and they didn't eat so much to sleep. They are fascinated if they see birds through the large window. Staff is well trained and friendly.

First they say 220 yen for 10 minutes, then it turns out that you need to buy a drink for a minimum of 350 yen.  Then the clock starts right away while you still have to stow away your gear and pick up slippers.  When you get in you go to a vending machine to get your drink, but 75% of the drinks available are completely sold out.  By the time you get your drink and sit down and actually take a pic or two of the kittens, your 10 minutes is up.  The place is modern, nice and clean.  There were a dozen kittens and two main rooms to hang out in, but the overall time allotted and the drink offerings were disappointing.  In my view - Not really worth it.

This spot features a nice view, cute decor, and is easy to find. It is standardly priced (about $2 for 10 minutes) but was crowded not really a place to relax. The cats are over exposed to people and frankly either try to get away from your touch or have zero interest in humans.

Funny cat cafe, if you are in Tokyo pay one of them a visit, it is a good laugh. This one in particular was very nicely made, the cats were quite playful, and the area they are in is prone to good times. You pay 200 yen per 10 minutes, plus a 350 yen all-you-can-drink fee from the cafeteria. We stayed 40 minutes, and left wanting to stay for more!

If you like cats and care about them, just don't go there!!!!!!!!
Beside the fact that it is super expensive, cats are COMPLETELY DRUGGED!!
Several of them were not even giving any reaction, sleeping in completely uncomfortable position the same way they do after an anesthesia...
Shame, I just regret I gave money to this animal cruelty!!!

reviews.text:
If I'm honest I'm very disappointed because the cats do not look in the best condition! Definitely not a cat cafe I would recommend, but the only thing that was good was the coffee.

Also this place is not wheelchair accessible or disabled friendly. There's no place to put the chair whilst you go inside and there's no disabled toilet. Basically I do not recommend for disabled tourists.

Cute little cat cafe in Akihabara. Free drinks and coffee during your stay using vending machines. There are tables where you can get some work done or beanbags with video game consoles where you can chill out. They're pretty strict on time so make sure you don't go over.
You must visit! I have never seen so many different kinds of cats. It is so clean here and the cats look well taken care of.

Nice cafe, good outlook on the city. Very strict on time limits, so you'll get charged for any extra minutes you take getting to the counter. Overall a nice experience, the cats were lovely and the interior is well designed

Nice space, and very well maintained. The cats were all docile and easy to interact with. We were there for 1 hour and purchased a treat popsicle,  and it cost about 4,000 yen. It's a bit more expensive than other options, but the clean facility makes it worth it.

reviews.text: large, cozy seating, massage chairs, friendlier cats than some places. Got some very cute photos.

This is a very relaxed place. Cats are everywhere, fluffy and cute. The big ones seem to always be napping and just laying around but a handful of kittens were running around and playing. The place is filled with everything you could need for a quiet afternoon: sofa, bed, massaging chair, wifi, manga library (Japanese), a Switch, ps4 with VR headset and a Nes. If you're in Ikebukuro you should check this place out.
One of the best cat cafe chains! Stylish, comfortable  and energetic cats. A great way to spend time :)
Not a crazy experience but and enjoyable one for $2. Pet a cat. Have a coffee amd chill.
Great place to relax for kids and cat lovers.

reviews.text:
Small neko cafe with a good atmosphere. It looks clean and doesn't smell. The cats get spaces where they can escape if they don't want to interact with people. 

Most of them are very patient with people. They're apparently around 5-10 years old so they're pretty quiet and sleep a lot. The cafe have quite a lot of tall and fluffy cats. 

The staff was very nice with us, they gave us information about the cats personalities and history, they helped us getting cats near us and they're very attentive to be sure nobody is treating the cats badly which I appreciated.

This place doesn't have any strong offensive smell despite there being so many cats. It's mandatory to wear indoor slippers (the the store provide them) and wash your hands before entering the cat area. Two stories/big rooms full of cute, playful, sleepy cats. Buy the chicken meat and the cats will come to you. I got a smart tabby to shake my hands for the treat.
My kids enjoyed playing with the cats! Lovely kitties and very nice ambiance. We came almost closing time at 8:30pm. But we still paid full price rate of 700.00 yen.

Very nice place to have a good rest after a long day at the same time relaxing with all the friendly cats. 
Highly recommended for cat person.

reviews.text: Great cafe. Staff are some of the friendliest I've meet and cats where really sweet. Very cheap as there is no seat charge. Highly recommended

Pretty typical price for tokyo. Staff were friendly. All you need to do is buy a drink here to play with the cats. The place is pretty clean but it has that cat smell. The cats seem pretty fed up of humans quite frankly so you can't really play with them much. Maybe they need some break during the week. The young cats do enjoy playing.

The shop is nice and cozy, cats are cute too. But this place is more like a place to drink coffee rather than a place to play with cats so it's a little not interesting. And the most important thing is the attitude of the staffs towards foreigners like me and my friends. Not friendly at all.
Pancakes were badly done and expensive. The staffs were not friendly and arrogant. Waste of time and money.

We stopped here for a drink. This is a nice small cafe.

There is no cover charge before 6pm (at least not for the hour we were there). 

The staff were friendly and had enough English to make up for our lack of Japanese.

The cats were very relaxed, but did like stealing your seat if you got up.
